1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,916
Imagine two answers in a review queue.

2
00:00:02,916 --> 00:00:09,164
One is excellent. It is clear, complete, and already near
the top of the scale.

3
00:00:09,164 --> 00:00:17,910
The other is shaky. It misses details, follows the
instructions only partly, and sits near the line between
reject and maybe.

4
00:00:17,910 --> 00:00:19,577
Now add a label.

5
00:00:19,577 --> 00:00:29,157
Not a real change to the answer. Just a displayed name. A
model name. A team name. A school name. A vendor name.

6
00:00:29,157 --> 00:00:32,905
Some cue the judge is not supposed to use.

7
00:00:32,905 --> 00:00:41,236
If that label creates bias, many people picture a simple
bonus: plus half a point for the favored label,
everywhere.

8
00:00:41,236 --> 00:00:44,568
But a more dangerous pattern can look different.

9
00:00:44,568 --> 00:00:49,150
The strong answer has nowhere to go. It was already high.

10
00:00:49,150 --> 00:00:52,482
The weak answer has room to be forgiven.

11
00:00:52,482 --> 00:00:58,313
So the label does not lift the whole scale evenly. It
raises the floor.

12
00:00:58,313 --> 00:01:01,645
This is the bias that looks like mercy.

13
00:01:01,645 --> 00:01:08,726
In the AI Village label-swap study, the same answers were
shown under different displayed author labels.

14
00:01:08,726 --> 00:01:14,141
That lets you ask a causal question: same work, different
label, different score?

15
00:01:14,141 --> 00:01:25,804
The answer was not the same for every judge. Gemini showed
the clearest displayed-self-label boost. GPT-5.5 was
exactly label-invariant in the paired slice.

16
00:01:25,804 --> 00:01:30,386
Claude and Kimi were smaller or noisier in this particular
test.

17
00:01:30,386 --> 00:01:34,967
But where label effects appeared, they often had an
important shape.

18
00:01:34,967 --> 00:01:42,465
The boost was not just a flat reward for the label. It was
larger on lower-scoring answers.

19
00:01:42,465 --> 00:01:54,544
A weak answer under a favorable label could get more
benefit of the doubt. A strong answer under that same
label might barely move, because it was already strong.

20
00:01:54,544 --> 00:01:58,293
That matters because real decisions often happen near
thresholds.

21
00:01:58,293 --> 00:02:03,707
If a score moves from 9.1 to 9.3, nothing may change.

22
00:02:03,707 --> 00:02:17,036
If a score moves from 5.8 to 6.2, the answer may cross
from fail to pass, reject to review, unsafe to maybe safe,
or below the leaderboard cutoff to above

23
00:02:17,036 --> 00:02:18,036
it.

24
00:02:18,036 --> 00:02:22,201
A small average effect can hide a big decision effect.

25
00:02:22,201 --> 00:02:28,033
This is why “the average label bias is only small” is not
enough comfort.

26
00:02:28,033 --> 00:02:30,115
Ask where the movement happens.

27
00:02:30,115 --> 00:02:32,614
Does it happen on borderline examples?

28
00:02:32,614 --> 00:02:35,114
Does it happen on weaker work?

29
00:02:35,114 --> 00:02:40,112
Does it happen in one task, language, model family, or
difficulty slice?

30
00:02:40,112 --> 00:02:46,360
Does it change pass-fail decisions, or only move scores
far from any action boundary?

31
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:51,358
A floor-raiser pattern also changes how you audit an AI
judge.

32
00:02:51,358 --> 00:02:56,356
Do not test only polished examples. Include messy,
mediocre, and borderline examples.

33
00:02:56,356 --> 00:03:03,021
Do not report only the mean score difference. Plot the
label effect against the baseline score.

34
00:03:03,021 --> 00:03:09,685
Do not ask only whether the judge is biased. Ask which
decisions the bias can change.

35
00:03:09,685 --> 00:03:20,098
And if labels are not supposed to matter, remove them
before scoring. Or at least run a paired label-swap audit
before trusting the scores.

36
00:03:20,098 --> 00:03:22,181
There is one more caution.

37
00:03:22,181 --> 00:03:33,843
Calling this mercy is a metaphor, not a mind-reading
claim. The model is not necessarily feeling sympathy. It
is producing scores under prompts, labels, and learned
patterns.

38
00:03:33,843 --> 00:03:41,757
But the operational effect can still look like mercy: weak
work gets softened when a favorable cue is present.

39
00:03:41,757 --> 00:03:44,256
For humans, the lesson is simple.

40
00:03:44,256 --> 00:03:48,838
Bias is not only about who gets the biggest average bonus.

41
00:03:48,838 --> 00:03:53,003
Bias is also about who gets rescued at the line.

42
00:03:53,003 --> 00:04:02,000
When an AI judge is part of a real decision, inspect the
floor, inspect the threshold, and inspect the examples
that almost changed.
